So then, the Delos-born1 did bear away that old king to the land of the Hyperboreans and there give him dwelling, him and his slender- ankled daughters, by reason of his piety, because he of all mankind had sent up the greatest gifts to hallowed Pytho.

Yet of all the dwellers that are in Greece,² O illustrious Hiero, no man can say that any hath given to Loxias3 so much gold as thou. If a man only batten not on envy, he will surely praise a favourite of Heaven, a lover of horses, a man os war, that holdeth the sceptre of the Lord of Laws, and eke hath share in the gifts of the violet-tressed Muses,—one who, though his hand was terrible once in war, looketh calmly now that he is old on a happiness that is from day to day, well knowing it to be short.
